
# Git Cheat Sheet for Developers
A practical reference of the most useful Git commands and workflow tips.

## ⚡ Most Common Git Workflow

git status
git add .
git commit -m "Describe change"
git push

## 📜 View Commit History
git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all

## 🔍 See File Changesgit diff
git diff

# 1. Basic Repository Setup

Initialize a repository:

    git init

Check repository status:

    git status

Add files to staging:

    git add .

Add a specific file:

    git add filename.py

Create a commit:

    git commit -m "Describe your change"

View commit history:

    git log

Compact history view:

    git log --oneline

---

# 2. Inspect Changes

Show changes not yet staged:

    git diff

Show changes staged for commit:

    git diff --staged

Show what changed in the last commit:

    git show

---

# 3. Branching (Core Professional Workflow)

List branches:

    git branch

Create a branch:

    git branch feature-name

Create and switch branch:

    git checkout -b feature-name

Switch branch:

    git checkout main

Merge branch into current branch:

    git merge feature-name

Delete a branch:

    git branch -d feature-name

---

# 4. Working With GitHub (Remote Repositories)

Add remote repository:

    git remote add origin REPO_URL

Rename branch to main:

    git branch -M main

Push code to GitHub:

    git push -u origin main

Push updates:

    git push

Pull latest changes:

    git pull

Fetch changes without merging:

    git fetch

---

# 5. Professional Daily Workflow

Typical workflow used by developers:

    git status
    git add .
    git commit -m "Explain the change"
    git push

---

# 6. Git History Visualization (Very Useful)

Visual history graph:

    git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all

Create a shortcut for this command:

    git config --global alias.tree "log --oneline --graph --decorate --all"

Then use:

    git tree

This gives you a visual map of your repository history.

---

# 7. Undoing Mistakes

Unstage a file:

    git restore --staged filename.py

Discard local changes:

    git restore filename.py

Reset last commit but keep changes:

    git reset --soft HEAD~1

Reset last commit completely:

    git reset --hard HEAD~1

---

# 8. Useful Debug Commands

Check active branch:

    git branch

Check remote repositories:

    git remote -v

---

# 9. Best Practices

✔ Make small commits  
✔ Write clear commit messages  
✔ Use branches for new features  
✔ Never commit secrets (.env files)  
✔ Always use a .gitignore file  

---

